Daniel Waterhouse is awakened at Trinity College in 1661 by a confrontation between a somber Puritan student and a group of flamboyant, aristocratic revelers.

**"The Dissenters are destitute of all decorations that can please the outward Senses"** — This refers to [English Dissenters](/topic/english-dissenters), Protestants who separated from the Church of England and favored an austere lifestyle that stood in stark contrast to the flamboyant Restoration court.

**"ANONYMOUS, ATTRIBUTED TO BERNARD MANDEVILLE, 1714"** — [Bernard Mandeville](/topic/bernard-mandeville) was an Anglo-Dutch philosopher and satirist famous for *The Fable of the Bees*, which controversially argued that "private vices" like greed and luxury actually produce "public benefits" by stimulating the economy.

**"The tail of Ursa Major was like the hand of a cœlestial clock"** — Before the era of reliable pocket watches, scholars used a [Nocturnal](/topic/nocturnal-timekeeping), an instrument that allowed them to determine the time at night by measuring the rotation of the "pointer" stars in Ursa Major around the North Star.

**"a black coat and black breeches with no decorations... others were flounced and feathered"** — This highlights the dramatic shift in [Restoration Fashion](/topic/restoration-london), where the "Plain Style" of the Puritan era was suddenly replaced by the extravagant, French-influenced "Cavalier" styles favored by the returning monarchy.

**"divines who were fluent in Greek and Latin and Hebrew"** — During this period, the [University Education](/topic/17th-century-university-education) at Cambridge and Oxford functioned primarily as a seminary for the Church of England, focusing on classical languages and theology rather than modern science.

**"The Duke of Monmouth picked the wench up"** — [James Scott, Duke of Monmouth](/topic/monmouth), was the eldest illegitimate son of Charles II; a charismatic but reckless figure, he would eventually lead a famous failed rebellion to seize the throne.

**"It’s Comstock and Jeffreys."** — George Jeffreys, later known as [Judge Jeffreys](/topic/judge-jeffreys), would become the notorious "Hanging Judge" known for his legal brilliance and extreme cruelty during the "Bloody Assizes."

**"Some Phanatique—a Puritan, or possibly a Barker"** — [Fanatics](/topic/puritans) was a derogatory term used during the Restoration to describe non-conformist Protestants perceived as religious extremists or political radicals.

**"spent the Interregnum in Paris"** — The [Interregnum](/topic/english-civil-war) was the period between the execution of Charles I in 1649 and the Restoration of 1660, during which England was a republic under Oliver Cromwell.

**"Academy of Monsieur du Plessis, near the Palais Cardinal"** — The [Academy of Monsieur du Plessis](/topic/academy-of-monsieur-du-plessis) was a prestigious Parisian riding and fencing school where young aristocrats were trained in the essential "arts of the courtier."

**"author of the recent Declaration of Uniformity"** — The [Act of Uniformity 1662](/topic/act-of-uniformity-1662) required all clergy to follow Anglican rites, leading to the "Great Ejection" of thousands of Puritan ministers from their positions.

**"jobless Ranters, Barkers, Quakers, et cetera"** — [Ranters](/topic/ranters) were a radical antinomian sect known for pantheistic views, while [Quakers](/topic/quakers) faced heavy persecution for refusing to swear oaths or recognize social hierarchies.

**"Anglicans of the Archbishop Laud school"** — [William Laud](/topic/william-laud), the Archbishop of Canterbury under Charles I, introduced "High Church" reforms that many Puritans feared were a secret move back toward Roman Catholicism.

**"spent rather a lot of time in the Dutch Republic"** — The [Dutch Republic](/topic/dutch-republic) was a 17th-century global power known for its maritime trade, scientific advancement, and a level of religious tolerance rare in Europe.

**"Upnor would be Judged—for good—five years from now when Jesus came back."** — Many 17th-century radicals embraced [Apocalypticism](/topic/apocalypticism), interpreting the year 1666 as the date of the Second Coming based on the "Number of the Beast" in the Book of Revelation.

**"The College of the Holy and Undivided Trinity did not segregate the classes as rigidly"** — [Trinity College, Cambridge](/topic/trinity-college-cambridge), founded by Henry VIII, was the academic home of Isaac Newton and a central site for the emerging scientific revolution.

**"Isaac was pale as starlight, and so frail-looking"** — This introduces [Isaac Newton](/topic/isaac-newton) as a student. Stephenson's annotation: "When Isaac was born he was so small that his mother commented that 'he might have been put into a quart mug' and so weak that no one thought he would live beyond a couple of days."

**"alienated Puritan with a secret interest in natural philosophy"** — [Natural Philosophy](/topic/natural-philosophy) was the precursor to modern science, encompassing the study of the physical universe before physics, chemistry, and biology became distinct disciplines.

**"working their separate ways through Aristotle"** — The Cambridge curriculum was still dominated by the ancient Greek philosopher [Aristotle](/topic/aristotle), whose logic and physics Newton would eventually famously reject.

**"radiant spirit allowed to shine forth, like the Philosophick Mercury"** — In [Alchemy](/topic/alchemy), "Philosophick Mercury" refers to a purified, "living" form of mercury believed to be the essential ingredient for creating the Philosopher's Stone.

**"Isaac was seated a few inches away. He had shoved a darning needle several inches into his eyeball."** — This describes [Newton's Eye Experiment](/topic/newton-eye-experiment), a real historical event where Newton probed his own eye socket with a "bodkin" to study how pressure affects color perception.

**"I’ve been reading Boyle’s latest—Experiments and Considerations Touching Colors"** — [Robert Boyle](/topic/robert-boyle) was a pioneer of the experimental method; his 1664 work, [*Experiments and Considerations Touching Colours*](/topic/experiments-and-considerations-touching-colours), was a primary influence on Newton’s own research.

**"as a lens put chromatic aberrations into all the light"** — [Chromatic Aberration](/topic/chromatic-aberration) is the failure of a lens to focus all colors to the same point; Newton’s attempt to solve this led to his invention of the reflecting telescope.

**"Heavenly radiance fills the æther"** — In 17th-century physics, the [Aether](/topic/aether-physics) was a hypothesized medium thought to fill all space and allow for the transmission of light and gravity.

**"Descartes gave us the plane."** — [René Descartes](/topic/rene-descartes) developed the Cartesian coordinate system, which revolutionized mathematics by allowing geometric shapes to be expressed as algebraic equations.

**"the moon that Christian Huygens had lately discovered"** — [Christiaan Huygens](/topic/christiaan-huygens) was a Dutch astronomer who discovered Saturn's largest moon, Titan, in 1655 and was the first to correctly identify Saturn's rings.

**"wrote Sins committed before Whitsunday 1662"** — This refers to [Newton's List of Sins](/topic/newtons-list-of-sins), a real historical document found in his notebooks where he recorded 49 various transgressions from his youth.
